Cape Town - President Jacob Zuma&apos;s office on Monday said it has lodged a complaint with the office of the Public Protector over the leaking of an audio recording of his interview with the former head of the institution, Thuli Madonsela, to the media&#x201C;The audio recording was leaked to the television channel eNCA,&#x201D; the presidency said. &#x201C;The presidency has sought clarity from the Office of the Public Protector on the policy of the institution regarding the release of audio recordings of interviews conducted during the course of investigations.The recording formed part of Madonsela&apos;s investigation into the Gupta family&apos;s business dealings with the state and allegations that it influenced executive decisions, including Cabinet appointments.Transcript of President Zuma&apos;s interview with Thuli MadonselaHer 355-page report flowing from the probe was released last week after Zuma abandoned a court bid to block it.The report contains a transcript of Madonsela&apos;s interview with Zuma in which he refused to answer questions.In her report Madonsela found that the president may have flouted the Executive Members Ethics Act and ordered him to appoint a commission of inquiry to continue the investigation. African News Agency IOL News on Facebook IOL on Twitter